{"title":"A Peek into Token Bias: Large Language Models Are Not Yet Genuine Reasoners","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Accuracy alone cannot tell whether LLMs genuinely reason or exploit superficial token patterns; we need a principled way to detect token bias in reasoning tasks.","method":"Proposes a hypothesis-testing framework that generates matched pairs of problems via systematic token perturbations that preserve underlying logic. It forms 2×2 contingency tables (n11, n12, n21, n22) and tests marginal homogeneity (π12=π21) using McNemar’s test (exact/normal) with Benjamini–Hochberg control across models. Predictable shifts (e.g., n12<n21 or n12>n21 per hypothesis) indicate token bias rather than genuine reasoning."},{"problem":"Existing benchmarks risk contamination and confounds; we need controlled data and perturbations to isolate specific token biases in logical reasoning.","method":"Builds carefully controlled synthetic datasets for conjunction fallacy, syllogistic fallacy, and a mathematical ‘twenty-five horses’ problem, then applies targeted token perturbations while holding logic fixed. Perturbations include: swapping contextually relevant conjuncts for irrelevant ones; altering classic exemplar names (Linda→Bob); replacing celebrity names with generic ones; rephrasing quantifiers (‘All’/‘Some’) with equivalents; reframing narratives by adding reputable/less reputable institutions; and leaking weak/strong hint tokens. Each perturbation is paired with a directional alternative hypothesis tailored to expose specific token biases."},{"problem":"It is unclear whether recent LLM gains on reasoning tasks reflect true reasoning or reliance on token cues and hints.","method":"Runs large-scale, controlled matched-pair evaluations across many LLMs (e.g., GPT-4/4o, Claude, LLaMA-3, Mistral) and prompting regimes (baseline, zero-/one-/few-shot with/without CoT). Finds statistically significant, directional performance shifts consistent with token bias: e.g., improved accuracy when misleading conjuncts are replaced by irrelevant ones; degraded accuracy when ‘Linda’ is changed to ‘Bob’; sensitivity to quantifier rephrasings; narrative framing effects; and strong gains from leaked hints—collectively indicating reliance on token bias rather than invariant reasoning."}]}
